{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pass 1: Integration, because the failure is at a module handoff boundary (classifier -> API client payload). MOCK-MISS: this is not just pure local logic; it verifies what is actually sent outward. Pass 2 downgrade check: Unit is possible only if behavior were limited to a pure payload-builder function, but the behavior text says \"request sent to the external API,\" so one-module-only scope is disqualified. Upgrade check: System rejected because behavior text does not require real network/OS/subprocess; an in-process fake client can assert payload contents. Agentic/Workflow rejected because no correctness dependence on model output quality or multi-agent sequence is stated.","test_description":"Wire classifier with a fake API client that records outgoing request body. Call classify(document). Assert recorded request contains every configured taxonomy label (no omissions) in the field/prompt used for classification.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pass 1: Integration, because failure appears when external response is handed into module validation/normalization logic. Pass 2 downgrade check: Unit would be enough only for an isolated mapping function, but behavior explicitly starts from \"When the API returns...\" which implies module interaction with client response shape. Upgrade check: System rejected by behavior text because no real network behavior is needed; stubbed response with invalid label reproduces failure. Agentic/Workflow rejected because this checks post-response guardrail logic, not model quality.","test_description":"Run classifier with stub API client returning a successful response containing an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"). Assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\" and not the raw label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pass 1: Agentic, because the behavior is about stability of classification outcomes across repeated calls and the decision is delegated to an external AI API. MOCK-HIDE: deterministic stubs would likely always pass and hide real model variability. Pass 2 downgrade check: System with a deterministic fake endpoint would not catch true non-deterministic model drift/variance, so lower level is insufficient. Upgrade check: Workflow rejected because behavior describes repeated single-step classification calls, not multiple distinct agentic stages in a pipeline.","test_description":"Against the real AI classification API, call classify(the_same_document) repeatedly (e.g., N runs under same config). Assert labels remain identical across runs; flag any divergence as failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Pass 1: System, because this behavior is about actual tokens consumed per call against an external API budget, which depends on real request/response accounting over real HTTP. MOCK-HIDE: local token-count stubs can miss true provider-side counting and envelope overhead. Pass 2 downgrade check: Integration is insufficient if it only checks estimated/local counts; behavior says \"tokens consumed,\" implying actual consumption outcome. Upgrade check: Agentic rejected because this is not about output quality/non-deterministic classification correctness; it is infrastructure/API accounting. Workflow rejected because only one call-step budget check is described.","test_description":"Execute classification for representative documents against the real API and read actual token usage from provider response/telemetry. Assert each call’s consumed tokens is <= configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pass 1: Integration, because failure boundary is retry orchestration across modules (error handling + backoff + second call). Pass 2 downgrade check: Unit is too low if it only tests backoff math in isolation; behavior requires end-to-end module reaction to API rate-limit signal and retry success path. Upgrade check: System rejected because real network/OS timing is not required to prove behavior; fake API can return rate-limit then success, and controllable clock/sleeper can verify wait+retry. Agentic/Workflow rejected since no model-output-quality dependency or multi-agent chain is stated.","test_description":"Use a fake API client scripted to return rate-limit error on first attempt and success on second. Use fake clock/sleep hook to assert a wait occurred before retry. Assert caller receives successful classification, not an immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
